{"title_page": "True Self", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = True Self\n| type       = album\n| artist     = [[SOiL]]\n| cover      = TrueSelf.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 2, 2006\n| recorded   = October\u2013November 2005\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Alternative metal]], [[hard rock]]\n| length     = 43:29\n| label      = [[DRT Entertainment]]\n| producer   = [[Ulrich Wild]]\n| prev_title = [[Redefine (Soil album)|Redefine]]\n| prev_year  = 2004\n| next_title = [[Picture Perfect (Soil album)|Picture Perfect]]\n| next_year  = 2009\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r832392|pure_url=yes}} link]\n}}\n'''''True Self''''' is the fourth studio album by the American [[heavy metal music|metal]] band [[SOiL]], first released in the U.S. on May 2, 2006. It is the band's first album with new vocalist [[A.J. Cavalier]], formerly of World In Pain and Diesel Machine; and their last album to feature rhythm guitarist [[Shaun Glass]]. ''True Self'' was leaked onto [[Peer-to-peer file sharing|P2P]] and [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent]] sites on March 4, almost two months before its official release. The album sold 4,000 copies in the US during its first week of release.\n\nA [[music video]] was filmed for \"Give It Up\" and released shortly before the album.\n\nIn promotion of the album, Soil did a European/USA tour with [[Staind]], USA tours with [[Sevendust]], [[10 Years (band)|10 Years]] and [[Godsmack]], as well as numerous UK and European festival and headline tours. Soil ended the cycle with their summer 2007 ''True Rock'' tour.<ref>Chris Harris and Jon Wiederhorn [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1554818/20070315/meshuggah.jhtml Metal File: Dark Tranquillity, Meshuggah, Clutch & More News That Rules] MTV.com (March 16, 2007). Retrieved on June 4, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks were recorded at Bombshelter Studios in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], except ''Give It Up'', ''Hear Me'', ''Until It's Over'' and ''Jaded'', which were recorded at Glenwood Studios, [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], [[California]], [[United States|USA]]\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column  = Guest Vocals\n| title1 = Fight for Life\n| extra1 = \n| length1 = 4:10\n| title2 = Give It Up\n| extra2 = [[Wayne Static]] of [[Static-X]]\n| length2 = 3:00\n| title3 = Pick Me Up\n| extra3 = \n| length3 = 3:12\n| title4 = The Last Chance\n| extra4 = \n| length4 = 4:17\n| title5 = True Self\n| extra5 = \n| length5 = 3:18\n| title6 = Hear Me\n| extra6 = \n| length6 = 3:57\n| title7 = Forever Dead\n| extra7 = [[Burton C. Bell]]\n| length7 = 3:12\n| title8 = Let Go\n| extra8 = \n| length8 = 3:49\n| title9 = Until It's Over\n| extra9 = \n| length9 = 2:58\n| title10 = Jaded\n| extra10 = \n| length10 = 2:37\n| title11 = Threw It Away\n| extra11 = \n| length11 = 3:27\n| title12 = One Last Song\n| extra12 = \n| length12 = 5:28\n|total_length = 43:25\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n===Soil===\n* [[AJ Cavalier]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Adam Zadel]] \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Shaun Glass]] \u2013 rhythm guitar\n* Tim King \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Tom Schofield]] \u2013 drums\n===Other===\n* [[Wayne Static]] \u2013 guest vocals on \"Give It Up\"\n* [[Burton C. Bell]] \u2013 guest vocals on \"Forever Dead\"\n\n* Stephen Jensen \u2013 art director, designer, photographer\n* Shaun Nowotnik \u2013 assistant to Stephen Jensen\n* Brian Vecchione \u2013 band photography\n* [[Ulrich Wild]] \u2013 producer, engineer, mixer\n* [[Ted Jensen]] \u2013 mastering\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mtv.com/videos/soil/84722/give-it-up.jhtml \"Give It Up\" music video]\n\n{{Soil (American band)}}\n\n[[Category:2006 albums]]\n[[Category:Soil (American band) albums]]\n[[Category:DRT Entertainment albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ulrich Wild]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = True Self\n| type       = album\n| artist     = [[SOiL]]\n| cover      = TrueSelf.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 2, 2006\n| recorded   = October\u2013November 2005\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Alternative metal]], [[hard rock]]\n| length     = 43:29\n| label      = [[DRT Entertainment]]\n| producer   = [[Ulrich Wild]]\n| prev_title = [[Redefine (Soil album)|Redefine]]\n| prev_year  = 2004\n| next_title = [[Picture Perfect (Soil album)|Picture Perfect]]\n| next_year  = 2009\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r832392|pure_url=yes}} link]\n}}\n'''''True Self''''' is the fourth studio album by the [[Chicago]] metal band [[SOiL]]. It was released in the US on May 2, 2006, via [[DRT Entertainment]]. This is the band's first album with new vocalist [[AJ Cavalier]], formerly of World In Pain and Diesel Machine; and their last album to feature rhythm guitarist [[Shaun Glass]]. ''True Self'' was leaked onto [[Peer-to-peer file sharing|P2P]] and [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BitTorrent]] sites on March 4, almost two months before its official release. The album sold 4,000 copies in the US during its first week of release.\n\nA [[music video]] was filmed for \"Give It Up\" and released shortly before the album.\n\nIn promotion of the album, Soil did a European/USA tour with Staind, USA tours with Sevendust, 10 Years and Godsmack, as well as numerous UK and European festival and headline tours. Soil ended the cycle with the summer 2007 True Rock Tour.<ref>Chris Harris and Jon Wiederhorn [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1554818/20070315/meshuggah.jhtml Metal File: Dark Tranquillity, Meshuggah, Clutch & More News That Rules] MTV.com (March 16, 2007). Retrieved on June 4, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks were recorded at Bombshelter Studios in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], except ''Give It Up'', ''Hear Me'', ''Until It's Over'' and ''Jaded'', which were recorded at Glenwood Studios, [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], [[California]], [[United States|USA]]\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column  = Guest Vocals\n| title1 = Fight for Life\n| extra1 = \n| length1 = 4:10\n| title2 = Give It Up\n| extra2 = [[Wayne Static]]\n| length2 = 3:00\n| title3 = Pick Me Up\n| extra3 = \n| length3 = 3:12\n| title4 = The Last Chance\n| extra4 = \n| length4 = 4:17\n| title5 = True Self\n| extra5 = \n| length5 = 3:18\n| title6 = Hear Me\n| extra6 = \n| length6 = 3:57\n| title7 = Forever Dead\n| extra7 = [[Burton C. Bell]]\n| length7 = 3:12\n| title8 = Let Go\n| extra8 = \n| length8 = 3:49\n| title9 = Until It's Over\n| extra9 = \n| length9 = 2:58\n| title10 = Jaded\n| extra10 = \n| length10 = 2:37\n| title11 = Threw It Away\n| extra11 = \n| length11 = 3:27\n| title12 = One Last Song\n| extra12 = \n| length12 = 5:28\n|total_length = 43:25\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n===Soil===\n* [[AJ Cavalier]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Adam Zadel]] \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Shaun Glass]] \u2013 rhythm guitar\n* Tim King \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Tom Schofield]] \u2013 drums\n===Other===\n* [[Wayne Static]] \u2013 guest vocals on \"Give It Up\"\n* [[Burton C. Bell]] \u2013 guest vocals on \"Forever Dead\"\n\n* Stephen Jensen \u2013 art director, designer, photographer\n* Shaun Nowotnik \u2013 assistant to Stephen Jensen\n* Brian Vecchione \u2013 band photography\n* [[Ulrich Wild]] \u2013 producer, engineer, mixer\n* [[Ted Jensen]] \u2013 mastering\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mtv.com/videos/soil/84722/give-it-up.jhtml \"Give It Up\" music video]\n\n{{Soil (American band)}}\n\n[[Category:2006 albums]]\n[[Category:Soil (American band) albums]]\n[[Category:DRT Entertainment albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ulrich Wild]]\n", "name_user": "Urgal", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/True_Self"}
{"title_page": "SS Josiah Parker", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=File:SS John W Brown.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Josiah Parker'' was a standard [[liberty ship]], similar to {{SS|John W. Brown}}, seen here.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=''Josiah Parker''\n|Ship namesake=[[Josiah Parker]]\n|Ship owner=[[War Shipping Administration]]<ref name=Browning>Browning, pp. 467\u201368.</ref>\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|USA|1912}} New Orleans\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Delta Shipbuilding Co, New Orleans\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=44<ref name=Colton>{{cite web|last=Colton |first=Tim |url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/4emergency/wwtwo/delta.htm |title=Delta Shipbuilding Company, New Orleans LA |work=Shipbuildinghistory.com |publisher=The Colton Company |accessdate=26 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829190614/http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/4emergency/wwtwo/delta.htm |archivedate=29 August 2008 }}</ref>\n|Ship way number=8<ref name=Colton />\n|Ship laid down=16 July 1942\n|Ship launched=26 September 1942\n|Ship completed=21 October 1942\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=scrapped 1964\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{Liberty ship class}}\n|Ship tonnage={{Liberty ship tonnage}}\n|Ship length={{Liberty ship length}}\n|Ship beam={{Liberty ship beam}}\n|Ship height={{convert|34|ft|8|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{Liberty ship draft}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion={{Liberty ship propulsion|8}}\n|Ship speed={{Liberty ship speed}}\n|Ship capacity={{Liberty ship cargo capacity}}\n|Ship crew={{Liberty ship complement}}\n|Ship armament={{Liberty ship armament}}\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''SS Josiah Parker''''' was a [[Liberty Ship]] built during [[World War II]] by [[Delta Shipbuilding Company]], [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], an EC2-S-C1 Type.<ref>{{Cite web\n| title = Liberty ships built by Delta Shipbuilding and J. A. Jones Construction during World War II\n| accessdate = 2013-11-10\n| url = http://www.usmm.org/l/deltajones.html\n}}</ref> The ship was named for [[Josiah Parker]] (1751 \u2013 1810), an American politician who was a member of the United States House of Representatives from [[Virginia]] in the First through Sixth United States Congresses. \n\nThe SS ''Josiah Parker's'' Official Number was 242368. It was owned by the United States [[War Shipping Administration]]. Its MC Hull No. was 0132.<ref name = \"deltashipbuilding\">{{Cite web\n| title = Liberty Ships built by the United States Maritime Commission in World War II\n| accessdate = 2013-11-10\n| url = http://www.usmm.org/libertyships.html\n}}</ref> It was laid down on July 16, 1942 and launched  September 26, 1942.<ref>{{Cite web\n| title = Delta Shipbuilding, New Orleans LA\n| accessdate = 2013-11-10\n| url = http://shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/4emergencylarge/wwtwo/delta.htm\n}}</ref>\n\n== Convoy UGS-37, 1944 ==\nSS ''Josiah Parker'' was one of the 37 ships carrying [[United States Navy Armed Guard]]s in Convoy UGS-37, April 11-12, 1944.\n<blockquote>\n\"They were some 35 miles east of [[Algiers]] near midnight of April 11 and 12 when an undetermined number of enemy planes attacked. No ship carrying Armed Guards was hit by the enemy, but several ships received minor damage from the gunfire of other ships. Practically all ships opened fire and the amount of flak falling was quite heavy ... The ''Josiah Parker'' reported an explosion on one of the escorts and indicated that she too was hit by shell fragments.\"<ref>{{Cite book\n| last = Office of Naval Operations\n| title = HyperWar: US Naval Admin in WW II: History of the Naval Armed Guard Afloat\n| chapter = Chapter VIII, Six Mediterranean Convoys\n| chapterurl = http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/Admin-Hist/173-ArmedGuards/173-AG-8.html\n}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe SS ''Josiah Parker'' was sold to private interests in 1947 and scrapped in 1964.<ref name = \"deltashipbuilding\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://usmaritimecommission.de/pictures.php?code=B0132e ''Deka'' (ex- ''Epinal'', ex- ''Josiah Parker'') at unknown date and location between December 1963 and May 1964]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Josiah Parker}}\n[[Category:Liberty ships]]\n[[Category:World War II merchant ships of the United States|J]]\n[[Category:1942 ships]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=File:SS John W Brown.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Josiah Parker'' was a standard [[liberty ship]], similar to {{SS|John W. Brown}}, seen here.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name=''Josiah Parker''\n|Ship namesake=[[Josiah Parker]]\n|Ship owner=[[War Shipping Administration]]<ref name=Browning>Browning, pp. 467\u201368.</ref>\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry={{flagicon|USA|1912}} New Orleans\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=Delta Shipbuilding Co, New Orleans\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=44<ref name=Colton>{{cite web|last=Colton |first=Tim |url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/4emergency/wwtwo/delta.htm |title=Delta Shipbuilding Company, New Orleans LA |work=Shipbuildinghistory.com |publisher=The Colton Company |accessdate=26 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080829190614/http://www.shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/4emergency/wwtwo/delta.htm |archivedate=29 August 2008 }}</ref>\n|Ship way number=8<ref name=Colton />\n|Ship laid down=16 July 1942\n|Ship launched=26-Sepember 1942\n|Ship completed=21-October 1942\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=scrapped 1964\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class={{Liberty ship class}}\n|Ship tonnage={{Liberty ship tonnage}}\n|Ship length={{Liberty ship length}}\n|Ship beam={{Liberty ship beam}}\n|Ship height={{convert|34|ft|8|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft={{Liberty ship draft}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion={{Liberty ship propulsion|8}}\n|Ship speed={{Liberty ship speed}}\n|Ship capacity={{Liberty ship cargo capacity}}\n|Ship crew={{Liberty ship complement}}\n|Ship armament={{Liberty ship armament}}\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''SS Josiah Parker''''' was a [[Liberty Ship]] built during [[World War II]] by [[Delta Shipbuilding Company]], [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]], an EC2-S-C1 Type.<ref>{{Cite web\n| title = Liberty ships built by Delta Shipbuilding and J. A. Jones Construction during World War II\n| accessdate = 2013-11-10\n| url = http://www.usmm.org/l/deltajones.html\n}}</ref> The ship was named for [[Josiah Parker]] (1751 \u2013 1810), an American politician who was a member of the United States House of Representatives from [[Virginia]] in the First through Sixth United States Congresses. \n\nThe SS ''Josiah Parker's'' Official Number was 242368. It was owned by the United States [[War Shipping Administration]]. Its MC Hull No. was 0132.<ref name = \"deltashipbuilding\">{{Cite web\n| title = Liberty Ships built by the United States Maritime Commission in World War II\n| accessdate = 2013-11-10\n| url = http://www.usmm.org/libertyships.html\n}}</ref> It was laid down on July 16, 1942 and launched  September 26, 1942.<ref>{{Cite web\n| title = Delta Shipbuilding, New Orleans LA\n| accessdate = 2013-11-10\n| url = http://shipbuildinghistory.com/history/shipyards/4emergencylarge/wwtwo/delta.htm\n}}</ref>\n\n== Convoy UGS-37, 1944 ==\nSS ''Josiah Parker'' was one of the 37 ships carrying [[United States Navy Armed Guard]]s in Convoy UGS-37, April 11-12, 1944.\n<blockquote>\n\"They were some 35 miles east of [[Algiers]] near midnight of April 11 and 12 when an undetermined number of enemy planes attacked. No ship carrying Armed Guards was hit by the enemy, but several ships received minor damage from the gunfire of other ships. Practically all ships opened fire and the amount of flak falling was quite heavy ... The ''Josiah Parker'' reported an explosion on one of the escorts and indicated that she too was hit by shell fragments.\"<ref>{{Cite book\n| last = Office of Naval Operations\n| title = HyperWar: US Naval Admin in WW II: History of the Naval Armed Guard Afloat\n| chapter = Chapter VIII, Six Mediterranean Convoys\n| chapterurl = http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USN/Admin-Hist/173-ArmedGuards/173-AG-8.html\n}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe SS ''Josiah Parker'' was sold to private interests in 1947 and scrapped in 1964.<ref name = \"deltashipbuilding\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://usmaritimecommission.de/pictures.php?code=B0132e ''Deka'' (ex- ''Epinal'', ex- ''Josiah Parker'') at unknown date and location between December 1963 and May 1964]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Josiah Parker}}\n[[Category:Liberty ships]]\n[[Category:World War II merchant ships of the United States|J]]\n[[Category:1942 ships]]\n", "name_user": "Lyndaship", "label": "safe", "comment": "format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SS_Josiah_Parker"}
